<section xml:id="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-factoring">

    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Factoring</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equations-using-zero-product-principle" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-check-solutions-for-quadratic-equations" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equation-applications" /></li>
            <!-- TODO: Remove trig functions from CCOG statements -->
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>We have learned how to factor trinomials like <m>x^2+5x+6</m> into <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>. This skill is needed to solve an equation like <m>x^2+5x+6=0</m>, which is called a <term>quadratic equation</term>, because its leading term has a degree of <m>2</m>.</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtube="2ZzuZvz33X0"/>
    </figure>

    <p>A physics class launches a tennis ball from a rooftop that is <m>96</m> feet above the ground. They fire it directly upward at a speed of <m>16</m> feet per second and measure the time it takes for the ball to hit the ground below. We can model the height of the tennis ball, <m>h</m>, in feet, with the quadratic equation, <m>h=-16t^2+16t+96</m>, where <m>t</m> represents the time in seconds after the launch. Using the model we can predict when the ball will hit the ground.</p>

    <!-- TODO: Can we make an image for this application? -->

    <p>The ground has a height of <m>0</m>, or <m>h=0</m>. We will substitute <m>0</m> for <m>h</m> in the equation and we have
        <me>-16t^2+16t+96=0</me>
    We need to solve this quadratic equation for <m>t</m> to find when the ball will hit the ground.</p>

    <p>Let's review how to solve linear equations. For example,<md>
        <mrow>2x-9\amp=1</mrow>
        <mrow>2x-9\addright{9}\amp=1\addright{9}</mrow>
        <mrow>2x\amp=10</mrow>
        <mrow>\frac{2x}{2}\amp=\frac{10}{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>x\amp=5</mrow>
    </md></p>

    <p>The key strategy for solving a linear equation is to separate the variable terms from the constant terms on either side of the equal sign. Let's try the same strategy to solve <m>-16t^2+16t+96=0</m>.
    <md>
        <mrow>-16t^2+16t+96\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16t^2+16t+96\subtractright{96}\amp=0\subtractright{96}</mrow>
        <mrow>-16t^2+16t\amp=-96</mrow>
    </md></p>

    <p>We are stuck here because there is no way to isolate the <m>t</m> or get rid of the square in <m>t^2</m>. This is why we learned how to factor. For example, if we factor <m>x^2+5x+6</m> into <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>, the factors are linear.</p>

    <p>Once we factor the polynomial in our example, we will be able to solve it using the linear factors. We will look for a common factor first, and see that we can factor out <m>-16</m>. Then we can finish factoring the trinomial:<md>
        <mrow>-16t^2+16t+96\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(t^2-t-6)\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(t+2)(t-3)\amp=0</mrow>
    </md></p>

    <p>In order to solve the equation, we need to understand a property:</p>

    <theorem xml:id="theorem-zero-product-property">
        <title>The Zero Product Property</title>
        <idx><h>The Zero Product Property</h></idx>
        <statement>
            <p>If the product of two or more numbers is equal to zero, then one of the numbers must be zero.</p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>To understand this property, let's look at a few products:
        <md>
            <mrow>4\cdot7\amp=28\amp\amp\amp-4\cdot7\amp=-28\amp\amp\amp4\cdot7\cdot3\amp=84</mrow>
            <mrow>4\cdot0\amp=0\amp\amp\amp-4\cdot0\amp=0\amp\amp\amp4\cdot0\cdot3\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>0\cdot7\amp=0\amp\amp\amp0\cdot(-7)\amp=0\amp\amp\amp4\cdot7\cdot0\amp=0</mrow>
        </md>
    If none of the factors are zero, it is impossible to get a product of zero. The only way to get a product of zero is if one of the factors is zero. This property is unique to the number zero and can be used no matter how many numbers are multiplied together.</p>

    <p>Now we can see the value of factoring. We have three factors in our equation <m>-16(t+2)(t-3)=0</m>. The first factor is the number <m>-16</m>. The second and third factors, <m>t+2</m> and <m>t-3</m> are expressions that represent numbers. Since the product of the three factors is equal to zero, one of the factors must be zero.</p>

    <p>Since <m>-16</m> cannot be <m>0</m>, either <m>t+2</m> or <m>t-3</m> must be <m>0</m>. This gives us two equations to solve: 
        <md>
            <mrow>t+2\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp t-3\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>t+2\subtractright{2}\amp=0\subtractright{2}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp t-3\addright{3}\amp=0\addright{3}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=-2\amp\amp\text{or}\amp t\amp=3</mrow>
        </md>
    We have found two solutions, <m>t=-2</m> and <m>t=3</m>. A quadratic equation will have two linear factors, not including any constants, so it can have up to two solutions.</p>

    <p>Let's check each of our two solutions <m>t=-2</m> and <m>t=3</m>:<md>
        <mrow>-16t^2+16t+96\amp=0\amp\amp\amp-16t^2+16t+96\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(-2)^2+16(-2)+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-16(3)^2+16(3)+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(4)-32+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-16(9)+48+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>-64-32+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-144+48+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>-96+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-96+96\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0\amp\amp\amp0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0</mrow>
    </md></p>

    <p>We have verified that our solutions are correct. While there are two solutions to the equation, the solution <m>t=-2</m> is not relevant to the physics model because it is a negative time. The solution <m>t=3</m> does make sense. According to the model, the tennis ball will hit the ground <m>3</m> seconds after it is launched.</p>

    <p>Here are a few more examples of solving quadratic equations. For problems without a context we will write the solutions in solution set notation.</p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2-5x-14=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><md>
                <mrow>x^2-5x-14\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-7)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x-7\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x-7\addright{7}\amp=0\addright{7}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\subtractright{2}\amp=0\subtractright{2}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=7\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-2</mrow></md>
                We write the solution set as <m>\{-2, 7\}.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>If the two factors of a polynomial happen to be the same, the equation will only have one solution. Let's look at an example of that.</p>

    <example>
        <title>A Quadratic Equation with Only One Solution</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2-10x+25=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><md>
                <mrow>x^2-10x+25\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-5)(x-5)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-5)^2\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x-5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x-5\addright{5}\amp=0\addright{5}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=5</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{5\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
            <p>We have now written solution sets for solving three different types of equations. A linear equation has a single solution, such as <m>\{-1\}</m>. A system of equations has one solution that is an ordered pair, such as <m>\{(-1,5)\}</m>. The parentheses indicate that the solution is an ordered pair. A quadratic equation can have up to two solutions. When it has two solutions it is written as <m>\{-1, 5\}</m>. We write the solutions in increasing order.</p>
        </remark>

    <p>Here is an example where we need to factor out a common factor first.</p>

    <example>
        <title>Factor Out a Common Factor</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>5x^2+55x+120=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><md>
                <mrow>5x^2+55x+120\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>5(x^2+11x+24)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>5(x+8)(x+3)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+8\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+3\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-3</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-8, -3\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>Here is an example where we will factor using the AC method.</p>

    <example>
        <title>Factoring Using the AC Method</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>3x^2-7x+2=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
                <p>Recall that we multiply <m>3\cdot2=6</m> and find a factor pair that multiplies to <m>6</m> and adds to <m>-7</m>. The factors are <m>-6</m> and <m>-1</m>. We use the two factors to replace the middle term with <m>-6x</m> and <m>-x</m>.<md>
                <mrow>3x^2-7x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>3x^2-6x-x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(3x^2-6x)+(-x+2)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>3x(x-2)-1(x-2)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(3x-1)(x-2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>3x-1\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>3x\amp=1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=\frac{1}{3}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{\frac{1}{3}, 2\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>So far the equations have been written in standard form, which is 
        <me>ax^2+bx+c=0</me>
    If an equation is not given in standard form then we must rearrange it in order to use the Zero Product Property.</p>

    <example>
        <title>Writing in Standard Form</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2-10x=24</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>To use the zero product property, we must have a zero on one side of the equation.<md>
                <mrow>x^2-10x\amp=24</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2-10x\subtractright{24}\amp=24\subtractright{24}</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2-10x-24\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-12)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x-12\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=12\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x=\amp-2</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-2, 12\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Writing in Standard Form</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>(x+4)(x-3)=18</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>This time we must multiply the left side and subtract <m>18</m> from both sides.<md>
                <mrow>(x+4)(x-3)\amp=18</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2+x-12\amp=18</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2+x-12\subtractright{18}\amp=18\subtractright{18}</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2+x-30\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x+6)(x-5)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+6\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-6\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=5</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-6, 5\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Factoring a Polynomial with Two Terms</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>2x^2=5x</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>It may be tempting to divide both sides of the equation by <m>x</m>; but if we did we would lose one of the solutions, <m>x=0</m>. Instead, we will put the equation in standard form.<md>
                <mrow>2x^2\amp=5x</mrow>
                <mrow>2x^2\subtractright{5x}\amp=5x\subtractright{5x}</mrow>
                <mrow>2x^2-5x\amp=0</mrow>
                <intertext>Since there are only two terms, we will look for a common factor.</intertext>
                <mrow>x(2x-5)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x-5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x\amp=5</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{5}{2}</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{0, \frac{5}{2}\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Factoring a Special Polynomial</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2=9</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>We will learn an easier method to solve this problem later. For now, we will put the equation in standard form and use factoring.<md>
                <mrow>x^2\amp=9</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2-9\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x+3)(x-3)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+3\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-3\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=3</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-3, 3\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Solving an Equation With a Higher Degree</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>2x^3-10x^2-28x=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Although this equation is not quadratic, it does factor so we can solve it by factoring.<md>
                <mrow>2x^3-10x^2-28x\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>2x(x^2-5x-14)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>2x(x-7)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>2x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-7\amp=0\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=7\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x\amp=-2</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-2, 0, 7\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>We will conclude this section with another application problem.</p>

    <example>
        <title>An Area Application</title>
        <!-- Is it possible to find a real-life example here? -->
        <statement>
            <p>Rajesh has a hot tub and he wants to build a deck around it. The hot tub is <quantity><mag>7</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> by <quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> and it is covered by a roof that is <quantity><mag>99</mag><unit base="foot" exp="2"/></quantity>. How wide can he make the deck so that it will be covered by the roof?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>We will define <m>x</m> to represent the width of the deck (in feet). Here is a diagram to help us understand the scenario.</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Diagram for the deck</caption>
                <image width="70%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw [color=blue] (1,1) rectangle (12,10);
                            \draw (3,3) rectangle (10,8);
                            \draw (6.5,3.5) node {$7$ ft};
                            \draw (9.5,5.5) node {$5$ ft};
                            \draw (6.5,2) node {$x$};
                            \draw (6.5,9) node {$x$};
                            \draw (2,5.5) node {$x$};
                            \draw (11,5.5) node {$x$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>The overall length is <m>7+2x</m> feet, because Rajesh is adding <m>x</m> feet on each side. Similarly, the overall width is <m>5+2x</m> feet.</p>

            <p>The formula for the area of a rectange is <m>\text{area}=\text{length}\cdot\text{width}</m>. Since the total area of the roof is <quantity><mag>99</mag><unit base="foot" exp="2"/></quantity>, we can write and solve the equation:<md>
                <mrow>(7+2x)(5+2x)=99</mrow>
                <mrow>4x^2+24x+35=99</mrow>
                <mrow>4x^2+24x+35\subtractright{99}\amp=99\subtractright{99}</mrow>
                <mrow>4x^2+24x-64\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>4(x^2+6x-16)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>4(x+8)(x-2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+8\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>Solution: Since a length cannot be negative, we take <m>x=2</m> as the solution. Rajesh should make the deck <quantity><mag>2</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> wide on each side to fit under the roof.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

